### Explanation

The use of multiple transaction managers of same priority (i.e., without `@Primary` annotation on one of them) in your Spring context is totally fine if you carefully look after their usages and always use the specific ones.

The error that you are facing is most probably due to use of `@Transactional` without specifying correct `transactionManager`. In this case, Spring Framework implicitly injects TransactionManager from the context (and assumes that there is a single match which is not your case).

It&#39;s worth looking through your project and / or its dependencies and you will probably find either a `@Transactional` method which is being called or explicit injection of a `@TransactionManager`.

### Example

For instance, suppose that you have a configuration
```
@Configuration
public class TransactionManagerConfig {

  @Bean
  public TransactionManager firstTransactionManager() {
    return new CustomTransactionManager();
  }

  @Bean
  public TransactionManager secondTransactionManager() {
    return new CustomTransactionManager();
  }
}
```
(where `CustomTransactionManager` is some your implementation)

and a repository with 2 methods which use each of the transaction managers:

```
@Repository
public class GeneralEntityRepository {

  @PersistenceContext
  private EntityManager entityManager;

  @Transactional(&quot;firstTransactionManager&quot;)
  public GeneralEntity getGeneralEntityWithId1() {
    return entityManager.find(GeneralEntity.class, 1);
  }

  @Transactional(&quot;secondTransactionManager&quot;)
  public GeneralEntity getGeneralEntityWithId2() {
    return entityManager.find(GeneralEntity.class, 2);
  }
}

```
then everything will work fine as Spring knows which manager to use.

However, if you add a third method without explicit transaction manager specification:
```
  @Transactional
  public GeneralEntity getGeneralEntityWithId3() {
    return entityManager.find(GeneralEntity.class, 2);
  }
```

then you will get an exception upon calling it:
```
// this is ok
GeneralEntity entity1 = generalEntityRepository.getGeneralEntityWithId1();

// this is also ok
GeneralEntity entity2 = generalEntityRepository.getGeneralEntityWithId2();
    
// this produces an exception
GeneralEntity entity3 = generalEntityRepository.getGeneralEntityWithId3();
System.out.println(&quot;GeneralEntity with id 3 = &quot; + entity3);
```

```
org.springframework.beans.factory.NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException: No qualifying bean of type &#39;org.springframework.transaction.TransactionManager&#39; available: expected single matching bean but found 2: firstTransactionManager,secondTransactionManager
```

This can be fixed by either specifying the transaction manager in `@Transactional` or by annotating one of them as `@Primary`.

See more information about `@Transactional` annotation in the official doc: https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/transaction/annotation/Transactional.html

I&#39;d say that it&#39;s up to you to decide, which one suits you best. Also, from what I know, some languages are encouraging to use a specific style:

**Java** prefers *[camelCase][1]* and 

    if (true) {
    }

**C#** *[PascalCase][1]* and 

    if (true)
    {
    }

However, it&#39;s important to keep the style consistent in the project. If you mix styles in a single file / project, that&#39;s bad practice.

  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camel_case

Although this is very much a matter of style, the &quot;Java way&quot; of doing it has always been to put the opening brace on the same line as the statement it is attached to. So

    if(condition) {
    }

is the suggested way of doing it. Who suggests this? Well, [Sun did][1] (and now Oracle maintains that page, too). And [Google does][2].


  [1]: http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/documentation/codeconventions-142311.html#449
  [2]: https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html#s4.1-braces

